<span id="freeTextContainer11632437876299040761">This book wasn&apos;t very well written and as the story progressed, it because more obvious that Peltier was guilty of killing the federal agents. He denies the crime throughout the book but came off much like Ted Bundy in &quot;Conversations With a Killer&quot;. He too maintained his innocence but gave away too much in the telling of the story.<br/><br/>It&apos;s true that Native Americans are still suffering but they would do better to try to improve their situations like the Choctaw did than to rally behind a murderous, </span>
  <span id="freeText11632437876299040761" style="display:none">This book wasn't very well written and as the story progressed, it because more obvious that Peltier was guilty of killing the federal agents. He denies the crime throughout the book but came off much like Ted Bundy in "Conversations With a Killer". He too maintained his innocence but gave away too much in the telling of the story.<br /><br />It's true that Native Americans are still suffering but they would do better to try to improve their situations like the Choctaw did than to rally behind a murderous, revolutionary felon. Leonard Peltier is no leader and does not deserve the accolades that he has been given.</span>
